European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the vertiginous rise in food prices.
The rise in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, recording - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, the Luxembourg-based Union Bureau of Statistics announced.
Official forecasts were only 3% likely, Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuer banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with the rising prices of commodities and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least near two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “We have to negotiate” on inflation so that it does not subsequently have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the 12-year record, while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation shot up in the euro area as a result of galoping food and energy prices.
Wheat term quotes increased by 88 percent and soybean quotes reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold nearly $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will decline to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup expects a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by the beginning of December support from the Young Democrats Alliance increased significantly, reaching its peak level since 2002, while the Gallup never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of Socialists.
The difference in the case of secure party voters – due to the increased firmness of opposition voters – would mean more than two-thirds (71 percent) of the support of a fifth of the socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary scan: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the secure voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest – it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country’s economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is fairly bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population is experiencing the deterioration of the situation and only one-tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those surveyed, higher than any previous Gallup survey, estimated that the President of Government performs his duties rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány heavily, while Viktor Orbán is supported by 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent does not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
