While after the October riots last year 35 percent estimated that it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation responded that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said they would likely participate.
In comparison, "a general election to be held on Sunday" would surely participate only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe it is likely to participate. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the outcome of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of education fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the secure participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of studies rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has fivefold its prices
The average price rise of 16 percent was maintained by hypermarkets in the Budaörs Gold Trade Triangle, with the difference that the VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs gold trading triangle the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above 1,000 HUF.
As in December last year prices in food supermarkets had already "fired", there was no dramatic increase in percentage compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously terrifying for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below HUF 9,000, today they can’t do it for even ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 that basket cost HUF 6,800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the same level as the previous year, but there was a sharp rise in turkey breast filet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we also found a kilogram of bread for the price of HUF 139.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the Coca-Cola with a two-liter redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, in the basket of Napi Auchan it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our estimates, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora rose by 15, while Tesco and Auchan rose by about 18 percent the prices in Napi’s basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was HUF 1206, so that during Christmas last year in prices the increase in VAT was felt.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visiblely unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the merchant poorly plans the speed of a product’s circulation, it may lose a significant profit on the margin that adjusts to the volume of sales.)
The rise in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which was the most expensive with HUF 1720 higher than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was just HUF 844.
Such extremes did not occur this year, since the highest price of now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, with hypermarkets growing more than 30 percent in the price of first-need consumer goods.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Office of Statistics: this office, in the case of some foodstuffs of first need, recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent over the 12-month interval.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst case only a 10 percent price increase.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic price increase even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the golden trade triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, carrying the preserved food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in-country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because incomes are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
Several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals this year due to the improper use of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, overcrowded beds and staff overload do not favor the control of infections - says the physician department chief of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago a MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred at the same hospital earlier this year.
One injured from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after he had to return to the hospital as a result of the contagion with MRSA and since then no major surgery has been performed due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multiresistant agents have been recorded in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, physician-head of department at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multiresistant agents has surely been recorded, for the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once exaggerated or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics turn into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and quickly infect under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, e.g. wound infections or sepsis in the first place for patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, for patients with the weakened body, for the elderly or for people with low weight.
In the opinion of the physician-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff cares for them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection can not be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multiresistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not in fashion.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come out in the public when MRSA infections already occur in the patient,” said the physician-head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous entrustments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for treating infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in ambulant patients or in basic care,” said Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in the washing of hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks, however also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favourable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher chance of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are met, fewer such infections are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treating MRSA is a huge expenditure for the National Disease Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fighting.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multiresistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Denial of police commander’s alcoholemia control that caused a deadly accident
The official expert report on the case of the deadly accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district has been made.
The possibility that he was driving drunk or in a stunned state can be excluded by the resigned police commander of the XXII district, who on Tuesday struck and caused the death of a passing person, said Attila Morvai, a spokesman for the Attorney General’s Office of the Capital, after preparing the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the outcome of the primary alcoholemia control that had already found that the former police commander did not drink alcohol before standing behind the wheel.
The then chief of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle folding into Kossuth Lajos Street of the XXII district, struck a 55-year-old man who intended to cross the street, but not in the pedestrian-designated area.
(This latter fact, i.e., that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give up the passage when folding.)
The passenger lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because it shook him greatly.
The investigation of the case is in charge of the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also said the former police commander from the outset collaborated with prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
€400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements worth €400 million in total in Budapest on Friday to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of €300 million to finance the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be implemented from the cohesion funds grant, of which the parties had previously signed a credit contract worth €100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining €200 million.
The €150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective from Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later, by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly spent on the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th Metro Line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalizes the details of the financing of the Metro with the EU, they will re-deal with the issue whether or not it is necessary to amend the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth €8.4 billion.
The interest of the credits is in line with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
