Fodor and the Six by Hundreds of Hungarians
As reported by Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the expert-level meetings will end Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the minister-level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Roadmap on post-emissions reduction efforts, set out in the Kyoto Protocol, which is in effect until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the particular issues between developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on accurate figures at the moment, although it tends to reach an agreement that compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020 the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF).
Six for hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit itself to decrease even by 30 percent if the other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to decrease greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will fulfill, notes the Ministry of the Environment’s press release.
This is a lot at stake in Bali, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise it is sure that its entry into force would be postponed after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its latest IPCC scientific report.
As a result, the reduction in emissions would be delayed and a rise of more than 2°C of the Earth’s average temperature could not be prevented, which scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
The British army units at a video distributor post recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the Kandahar General Operations Corps, then sent to London to be loaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded this way to the Internet and its "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
The air force had originally loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present the public the true goal of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the accurately edited and censored recordings, there are also amateur videos on the distributor, for example about the deaths of the soldiers: in the propaganda films "officials", a little hypocritical, officers speak of maximum losses, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet, but the British army is only lately taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with freely downloadable shooting video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can get directly instead of the soldiers.
