The party is not always written with red numbers.
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around holidays - that next year will be less - work days are reorganized.
Not even in the EU or North America are feasts united.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holidays, state holidays and holidays.
The holidays are mainly related to religious holidays and historical ephemerals.
We also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter especially so that those who have spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven holidays written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the 1848 revolution and October 23, commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20 we celebrate the foundation of the State, on May 1st the feast of work, on November 1st and 2nd we remind our deceased family and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day holidays the Easter of the Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, which is why it is often bridged when before or after the holiday there is a single working day.
In exchange for the extended weekends so, on the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labour that regulates in his specific decree when work is to be done exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or post-festival.
This legal standard is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory for companies and services institutions who, due to their function, work uninterruptedly even during holidays.
This year the order of work can only be altered around the holidays of the year: from December 24, life in the country is practically stopped, as according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
The next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First the agenda around the work party will be changed so that then, for four consecutive days, the workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26th will be working day, so in return Friday, May 2nd will be holiday day.
The other change is related to the October 23 feast: on Saturday, October 18, we will have to work instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, the next year will be able to rest during the holiday of the year, since from 24 December it will work almost nowhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
