After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen’s Nazi archives, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million documents of files, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far not accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of its management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research "particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as supposed homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or subjected countrymen in compulsory work and, eventually, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
