New fears about gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over gas prices between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect Russia’s export of fuel to Western Europe.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so every friction between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases gas prices, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
A previous dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, monopolic gas owner, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money that Ukraine was to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it will charge Ukraine more, as Ukraine has pledged to pay an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say Ukraine could pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transits during the talks,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
“The changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] through Ukraine.”
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly rose prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supply of gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS "should test foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to monitor the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchman said.
The recommendation of Auditor General Robert Black came after it was found that a foreign doctor was related to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of how much foreign staff it has.
However, his report noted other checks that are correctly carried out through a sample of five health authorities.
The general auditor checked the number of foreign personnel hired outside the European Economic Area following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi physician from Paisley’s Royal Alexandra Hospital, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep at the doors of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, accused of alleged car bombings in the UK.
NHS expects to conduct pre-employment checks on applicants, to make sure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish health board uses "Disclosure Scotland" to conduct criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The general auditor’s report recommends, among other measures, that boards should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which assists employers with criminal checks in many countries outside of Britain.
“Although we find some of the personal records with evidence of these checks, this is not a routine review,” the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: “Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of NHS foreign staff.”
Scottish BMA Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was “very unlikely” that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report suggests that pre-employment checks work at NHS Scotland but it is unclear what the added value of the recommendations made is,” he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign people, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the general auditor warned that the number may be higher, partly because boards have trouble identifying employees with indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely fulfilled.
This includes passport controls, work permits, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing foreigners’ pre-employment policy and guidelines in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was very interested that this work would be carried out in the wake of the terrorist attack on Glasgow airport.
He added that the Scottish government, together with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups – including foreigners – which they planned to publish next month.
