Venus climate can give an idea of the future of Earth
Venus may once have been an appropriate place for life, scientists declared yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like a Earth twin than had previously been observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane winds and storms of lightning.
The results of the European Space Agency for Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a picture of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes due to climate.
Professor Fred Taylor of the University of Oxford Department of Physics and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, states: “It is being clarified why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when two planets are so similar.
“Our new data make it possible to build a scenario where Venus began as Earth, possibly with a living environment millions of years ago.”
