Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Despite its atmosphere not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most Earth-like, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls in the poles, the same that also appear in winter on Earth.
Three decades ago, researchers had been suspected that there could be lightning on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays shut down at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, rays caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus, it’s not like that: if there was life there ever, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures reign 500°C, swinging in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Positively, Venus is a 'devil' twin of Earth, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, just for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles in Nature, according to the researchers, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had supposed,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers also discovered a cloud-formed vortex in the southern polar region that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds of wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits around the Sun almost 225 days.
But their rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble Earth much, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On both planets water had been clustered that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
