It's not wooden boxes.
Whoever relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but doesn’t think of Andy Warhol.
Or do you?
Currently, the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol’s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Brightness Box on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's "Bright-Box" market of 1968, the Moderna Museet of Stockholm also conducted internal research and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Bright-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hultén almost presented to the Modern Museet's.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Bright-Boxes" in New York, painting the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had soap powder boxes "Bright".
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Moderna Museet museum hundreds of Bright-carton boxes were exhibited. These were not made by Warhol (on account of expenses), but were brought directly from the "Bright" carton factory.
They were not works of art, but exemplars (which were only objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museum.
Witnesses of that time now talk about nearly fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Brightness Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
Some of them were bought at auctions for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed nearly one hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Moderna Museet museum, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies of 1990 shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight silver. In addition, it is not oil painting, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Bright-Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet museum, adding that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York City does not come to any conclusion, the Moderna Museet museum will classify these six boxes as copies.
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious allegations" that they are soap powder boxes.
But from that moment everything remained in absolute silence.
